Subject: [PATCH] core_validation: accept any alias-introducing extension for aliased XrStructureType values and aliased structs

OpenXR's core_validation API layer generates a per-XrStructureType
permission table from xr.xml: for each enum value (and each child
struct in a polymorphic relation group) owned by an extension, it
requires that extension to be enabled before the value/struct may
appear in any API call. The generator
(src/scripts/validation_layer_generator.py) emits a single
ExtensionEnabled() check using only the canonical value's owning
extension and ignores aliases.

This breaks every Khronos-style "_2"/"_FB"/"_EXT" extension whose
struct typedef is an alias of an earlier extension's struct (i.e.
they share the same numeric XrStructureType). The most common case
in the wild is XrGraphicsBindingVulkan2KHR
(XR_KHR_vulkan_enable2): its XR_TYPE_GRAPHICS_BINDING_VULKAN2_KHR
is `= XR_TYPE_GRAPHICS_BINDING_VULKAN_KHR` (line 946 of openxr.h),
so when an app correctly enables only XR_KHR_vulkan_enable2 and
passes a Vulkan2 binding to xrCreateSession, core_validation walks
the next-chain (via api_dump's xrStructureTypeToString output),
sees the canonical V1 type, demands XR_KHR_vulkan_enable, and
issues VUID-xrStructureTypeToString-value-parameter -- a false
positive that any "warnings are fatal" debug callback escalates
to a hard abort during session creation.

Same shape affects XR_TYPE_SWAPCHAIN_IMAGE_VULKAN_KHR /
XR_TYPE_GRAPHICS_REQUIREMENTS_VULKAN_KHR (also aliased by
XR_KHR_vulkan_enable2), and any future _2/_3 extension that adds
typedef aliases of an existing struct. There are two emission
sites: one in ValidateXrEnum (per-enum-value check) and one in
ValidateXrChildStruct (per-child-struct in relation groups, used
to validate polymorphic next-chain payloads).

Fix:
1. automatic_source_generator.py: capture the owning extension of
   each aliased struct in a new self.alias_ext_names dict. The
   struct's own ext_name records only the canonical extension;
   without this dict the aliased struct's ext info is otherwise
   silently dropped on the early-return path in genType.
2. validation_layer_generator.py / outputValidationSourceEnumValues:
   for each XrStructureType case, scan enum_tuple.values for every
   alias whose `.alias` resolves back to the canonical name and
   collect each alias's owning extension. The generated check then
   accepts any one of those extensions; the error message lists
   all of them.
3. validation_layer_generator.py / per-child-struct relation-group
   check: same shape, but iterate self.aliases (struct-name -> canonical
   struct name) and look up each alias's ext via self.alias_ext_names.

No behavioural change for enum values or structs without aliases
(accepted_exts collapses to the original single-extension list).

This is a downstream-local patch carried via CPM PATCHES until the
upstream fix lands in OpenXR-SDK-Source.
---
diff --git a/src/scripts/automatic_source_generator.py b/src/scripts/automatic_source_generator.py
--- a/src/scripts/automatic_source_generator.py
+++ b/src/scripts/automatic_source_generator.py
@@ -489,7 +489,13 @@
         # A list of all the API states
         self.api_states = []
         # A mapping of all aliases
         self.aliases = {}
+        # A mapping of struct/enum-value alias names to the extension that
+        # introduces them. The aliased entity's own ext_name records only
+        # the canonical (V1) extension; without this, aliased structs
+        # (e.g. XrSwapchainImageVulkan2KHR introduced by
+        # XR_KHR_vulkan_enable2) lose their owning extension.
+        self.alias_ext_names = {}
         # Max lengths for various items
         self.max_extension_name_length = 32
         self.max_structure_type_length = 32
@@ -908,3 +914,10 @@
         if alias:
             self.aliases[type_name] = alias
+            # Capture the alias's own owning extension. The full
+            # StructUnionData entry is dropped on the early-return below
+            # (only the canonical struct ends up in self.api_structures),
+            # so without this lookup we cannot tell that, say,
+            # XrSwapchainImageVulkan2KHR was introduced by
+            # XR_KHR_vulkan_enable2 rather than by XR_KHR_vulkan_enable.
+            self.alias_ext_names[type_name] = self.currentExtension
             return
diff --git a/src/scripts/validation_layer_generator.py b/src/scripts/validation_layer_generator.py
--- a/src/scripts/validation_layer_generator.py
+++ b/src/scripts/validation_layer_generator.py
@@ -351,12 +351,34 @@
                 enum_value_validate += self.writeIndent(indent)
                 enum_value_validate += f'case {cur_value.name}:\n'
                 if cur_value.ext_name and cur_value.ext_name != checked_extension and not self.isCoreExtensionName(cur_value.ext_name):
+                    # Aliased XrStructureType values share the same numeric
+                    # enum value, so any one of the alias-introducing
+                    # extensions also satisfies the dependency. Without
+                    # this, e.g. an app enabling only XR_KHR_vulkan_enable2
+                    # and passing XrGraphicsBindingVulkan2KHR (whose
+                    # XR_TYPE_GRAPHICS_BINDING_VULKAN2_KHR is `=
+                    # XR_TYPE_GRAPHICS_BINDING_VULKAN_KHR`) would
+                    # incorrectly fail this check because the canonical
+                    # value is owned by XR_KHR_vulkan_enable (V1).
+                    accepted_exts = [cur_value.ext_name]
+                    for other in enum_tuple.values:
+                        if (
+                            other.alias == cur_value.name and other.ext_name and
+                            other.ext_name != checked_extension and
+                            not self.isCoreExtensionName(other.ext_name) and
+                            other.ext_name not in accepted_exts
+                        ):
+                            accepted_exts.append(other.ext_name)
+                    ext_disjunction = ' or '.join(f'\\"{e}\\"' for e in accepted_exts)
                     indent += 1
                     enum_value_validate += self.writeIndent(indent)
-                    enum_value_validate += '// Enum value %s requires extension %s, so check that it is enabled\n' % (
-                        cur_value.name, cur_value.ext_name)
+                    enum_value_validate += '// Enum value %s requires extension(s) %s, so check that at least one is enabled\n' % (
+                        cur_value.name, ', '.join(accepted_exts))
                     enum_value_validate += self.writeIndent(indent)
-                    enum_value_validate += 'if (nullptr != instance_info && !ExtensionEnabled(instance_info->enabled_extensions, "%s")) {\n' % cur_value.ext_name
+                    enum_value_validate += 'if (nullptr != instance_info'
+                    for ext in accepted_exts:
+                        enum_value_validate += ' && !ExtensionEnabled(instance_info->enabled_extensions, "%s")' % ext
+                    enum_value_validate += ') {\n'
                     indent += 1
                     enum_value_validate += self.writeIndent(indent)
                     enum_value_validate += 'std::string vuid = "VUID-";\n'
@@ -374,7 +396,7 @@
                     enum_value_validate += self.writeIndent(indent)
                     enum_value_validate += 'error_str += " being used, which requires extension ";\n'
                     enum_value_validate += self.writeIndent(indent)
-                    enum_value_validate += f'error_str += " \\"{cur_value.ext_name}\\" to be enabled, but it is not enabled";\n'
+                    enum_value_validate += f'error_str += " {ext_disjunction} to be enabled, but it is not enabled";\n'
                     enum_value_validate += self.writeIndent(indent)
                     enum_value_validate += 'CoreValidLogMessage(instance_info, vuid,\n'
                     enum_value_validate += self.writeIndent(indent)
@@ -2046,11 +2068,26 @@
                     if child_struct and child_struct.ext_name and not self.isCoreExtensionName(child_struct.ext_name):
+                        # Aliased child structs share the canonical's
+                        # XrStructureType, so any alias-introducing
+                        # extension also satisfies the dependency. See
+                        # the enum-value comment above for the V2 binding
+                        # case that motivated this.
+                        accepted_exts = [child_struct.ext_name]
+                        for alias_name, target_name in self.aliases.items():
+                            if target_name == child:
+                                ext = self.alias_ext_names.get(alias_name)
+                                if ext and ext != child_struct.ext_name and not self.isCoreExtensionName(ext) and ext not in accepted_exts:
+                                    accepted_exts.append(ext)
+                        ext_disjunction = ' or '.join(f'\\"{e}\\"' for e in accepted_exts)
                         struct_check += self.writeIndent(indent)
-                        struct_check += 'if (nullptr != instance_info && !ExtensionEnabled(instance_info->enabled_extensions, "%s")) {\n' % child_struct.ext_name
+                        struct_check += 'if (nullptr != instance_info'
+                        for ext in accepted_exts:
+                            struct_check += ' && !ExtensionEnabled(instance_info->enabled_extensions, "%s")' % ext
+                        struct_check += ') {\n'
                         indent += 1
                         struct_check += self.writeIndent(indent)
                         struct_check += f'std::string error_str = "{xr_struct.name} being used with child struct type ";\n'
                         struct_check += self.writeIndent(indent)
                         struct_check += f'error_str += "\\"{self.genXrStructureType(child)}\\"";\n'
                         struct_check += self.writeIndent(indent)
-                        struct_check += f'error_str += " which requires extension \\"{child_struct.ext_name}\\" to be enabled, but it is not enabled";\n'
+                        struct_check += f'error_str += " which requires extension {ext_disjunction} to be enabled, but it is not enabled";\n'
                         struct_check += self.writeIndent(indent)
